BIOGRAPHY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Vincenzo Librandi was born on March 7, 1867, in Vaccarizzo Albanese, a small
town in the province of Cosenza, Calabria, Italy. Vaccarizzo Albanese is one
of the many Arbëreshë communities in southern Italy - settlements established
by Albanian refugees who fled the Ottoman invasion of the Balkans between the
15th and 18th centuries.

The Arbëreshë (also known as Italo-Albanians) are an ethnic-linguistic minority
who have preserved their Albanian language, culture, and traditions for
centuries in their Italian homeland. They speak an archaic variant of the
Tosk Albanian dialect, heavily influenced by the local Italian dialects.

EARLY LIFE AND EDUCATION:
-------------------------
Little is known about Librandi's early childhood in Vaccarizzo Albanese. The
next documented period of his life came when he left his family home to pursue
his studies. After obtaining authorization to retake his maturity exam
(esame di maturità), he successfully completed his education.

PROFESSIONAL CAREER:
--------------------
In 1890/1891, Librandi found employment as an "istitutore" (a tutor or
instructor) in Barcellona Pozzo di Gotto, a town in the province of Messina,
Sicily. This marked the beginning of what he himself described as twenty-two
years of "peregrinaggio" (pilgrimage/wandering) "da un Istituto ad un altro
della Peninsola" (from one Institute to another of the Peninsula).

This period of his life was characterized by constant movement across Italy,
working in various educational institutions throughout the country. Such
mobility was not uncommon for educators of his era, especially those from
southern Italy seeking better opportunities.

LATER LIFE AND DEATH:
---------------------
Vincenzo Librandi died on August 20, 1932, in Pineto, a coastal town in the
province of Teramo, Abruzzo region. The circumstances of his final years and
the reasons for his presence in Pineto remain largely undocumented in available
sources.

